{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532833"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14722"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14722"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.61,0.16,0.09,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107235"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7415"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89690"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2015"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39792"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107235"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with a one-day history of fever, severe myalgia, productive cough, and marked fatigue. She reports a decrease in her oral intake and has become increasingly short of breath. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Her regular medications include metformin, gliclazide, and tiotropium inhaler. Influenza is currently epidemic in the community.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and lethargic. Her pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. She has bilateral scattered wheeze and coarse crackles on chest auscultation. A chest x-ray shows bilateral patchy infiltrates in the lower zones. A rapid influenza antigen test is positive for influenza A.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Piperacillin-tazobactam","Oral oseltamivir","Ceftriaxone and azithromycin","Benzylpenicillin and doxycycline","Oral valaciclovir"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe symptoms of influenza during an epidemic period, confirmed by rapid antigen testing. She has multiple risk factors for severe disease, including age 65 years or older and significant comorbidities (diabetes and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease). Her clinical features suggest a significant illness requiring prompt treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral oseltamivir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral for influenza A. However, given the potential adverse events (e.g., neuropsychiatric symptoms), careful selection of patients who are likely to benefit from oseltamivir is required. This includes patients with established complications, requiring in-hospital management, or with moderate or high-severity community-acquired pneumonia. Treatment should also be considered in patients at heightened risk of poor outcomes, including pregnant women, adults \u003Cstrong\u003E\u2265 \u003C/strong\u003E65 years old, and certain conditions such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. If indicated, oseltamivir should be commenced as soon as possible, ideally within 48 hours of symptom onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPiperacillin-tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as initial therapy as there is no evidence of bacterial infection. It would not address the influenza A. It is a broad-spectrum antibiotics used in situations such as febrile neutropenia, Pseudomonas sepsis, and hospital-acquired pneumonia of high severity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone and azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the primary viral infection. This is an empirical therapy regimen for community-acquired pneumonia of severe severity. While empiric antibiotics may be considered if secondary bacterial pneumonia is suspected, antiviral therapy is the initial treatment of choice in this case of confirmed influenza.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzylpenicillin and doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered for community-acquired pneumonia of moderate severity but would not address the primary viral infection. The priority is to treat the confirmed influenza infection with appropriate antiviral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValaciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used primarily for herpes simplex and varicella-zoster infections. It would not be effective against influenza virus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to managing influenza is early recognition and prompt initiation of appropriate antiviral therapy in select patients. Risk factors for severe disease include age \u0026gt;65 years, pregnancy, immunosuppression, chronic respiratory disease, diabetes, and cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oseltamivir, if indicated, should be commenced within 48 hours of symptom onset in patients with severe influenza.","Risk factors for severe influenza include age \u226565 years, pregnancy, immunosuppression, and some chronic medical conditions."],"references":["Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {26 Oct 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au","Uyeki TM, Hui DS, Zambon M, Wentworth DE, Monto AS. Influenza. Lancet. 2022;400(10353):693-706. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(22)00982-5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T17:23:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T17:23:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7415"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107235"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"headin